questionText: What is the purpose of the 'volatile' keyword in Java?
option1: To indicate that a variable's value will be accessed by multiple threads
option3: To prevent a variable from being accessed by multiple threads
option4: To force garbage collection on a variable
correctOption: To indicate that a variable's value will be accessed by multiple threads

questionText: What are the differences between ArrayList and LinkedList in Java?
option1: ArrayList uses a dynamic array while LinkedList uses a doubly-linked list
option2: ArrayList is faster for accessing elements by index while LinkedList is faster for adding and removing elements
option3: ArrayList is faster for adding and removing elements while LinkedList is faster for accessing elements by index
option4: There are no differences between ArrayList and LinkedList
correctOption: ArrayList is faster for accessing elements by index while LinkedList is faster for adding and removing elements

questionText: What is the purpose of the 'transient' keyword in Java?
option1: To indicate that a variable should not be serialized
option2: To indicate that a variable should be initialized to its default value
option3: To indicate that a variable should be visible to all threads
option4: To indicate that a variable should be shared among all instances of a class
correctOption: To indicate that a variable should not be serialized

questionText: What are checked and unchecked exceptions in Java?
option1: Checked exceptions are subclasses of RuntimeException while unchecked exceptions are not
option2: Checked exceptions are not subclasses of RuntimeException while unchecked exceptions are
option3: Checked exceptions are errors that occur at runtime while unchecked exceptions are caught by the compiler
option4: There are no differences between checked and unchecked exceptions
correctOption: Checked exceptions are not subclasses of RuntimeException while unchecked exceptions are not

questionText: What is the purpose of the 'super' keyword in Java?
option1: To refer to the current instance of the class
option2: To refer to the superclass of the current class
option3: To refer to the subclass of the current class
option4: To refer to the parent class of the current class
correctOption: To refer to the superclass of the current class

questionText: What is the difference between 'throw' and 'throws' in Java?
option1: 'throw' is used to declare an exception while 'throws' is used to throw an exception
option2: 'throws' is used to declare an exception while 'throw' is used to throw an exception
option3: There is no difference between 'throw' and 'throws'
correctOption: 'throw' is used to declare an exception while 'throws' is used to throw an exception

questionText: What is the purpose of the 'this' keyword in Java?
option1: To refer to the superclass of the current class
option2: To refer to the subclass of the current class
option3: To refer to the current instance of the class
option4: To refer to the parent class of the current class
correctOption: To refer to the current instance of the class

questionText: What is the difference between 'abstract class' and 'interface' in Java?
option1: An abstract class can have constructors while an interface cannot
option2: An abstract class can have static methods while an interface cannot
option3: An abstract class can have final methods while an interface cannot
option4: There is no difference between abstract class and interface
correctOption: An abstract class can have constructors while an interface cannot

questionText: What is the purpose of the 'static' keyword in Java?
option2: To indicate that a variable's value will be accessed by multiple threads
option3: To indicate that a variable belongs to the class rather than to any instance of the class
correctOption: To indicate that a variable belongs to the class rather than to any instance of the class
